segments.text: June the 19th, in Fort Worth, having the pleasure of talking to Jim Creel.
Jim, you grew up where?
Most of my early years were in Denton.
My father was city manager there, and then about the time I was about 10 years old, we moved forward, and I've been here ever since.
I came back here after getting out of school and have been practicing law basically here ever since then.
The first important question.
Why did you attend Texas A&M?
Well, I have always...
had people say, well, you've never had any choice.
I don't know that that's true.
I did have a choice.
But my dad had gone there.
My mother had worked there before the war.
And I used to tell people that, jokingly, that my parents supported A&M before they supported me.
And I also knew
just enough about it to want to go there.
And I knew just enough.
I knew little enough about it that I didn't think I knew everything that I would find.
So I'd always had the plan to go there.
And I'm always typically glad I did.
You had visited there a number of times before you enrolled.
I'd been there with my folks primarily.
and thought I knew something about it.
When I got there my first year in the Corps, I decided I didn't know anything about it.
And maybe I made a bad decision.
But no, I felt like I knew what I was getting into.
Describe for me the trip down there when you're going to enroll.
How did you get there?
What did you take with you?
What gear?
What baggage?
I remember that my parents took me there.
They took me in the family car, and we unloaded just the things that we'd been told to bring, the basic essentials.
I had gone down there in the summer earlier.
In fact, I went to summer school in Junction before that.
And then I went to the orientation.
freshman orientation at A&M.
And I went there by myself because I thought I had it all figured out.
But my parents took me down there in September of 1965.
And it dropped me off.
And I think after that, reality hit me.
This was for real.
Describe the campus when you arrived.
What was there?
The only thing I really remember about it at Haskell was that we approached the core dorm area and there were lots of people who I thought were about like me already out in the area.
They'd already had some of the freshmen out marching and drilling.
I got moved in and I went over to the MSC and got my
Fish haircut, which I still remember my mother was aghast at.
But that's the main thing that I remember that particular time.
I remember that it was hot.
Mid-September is always hot, of course.
But that's my initial impression.
I wasn't thinking much about the campus.
I was just thinking about moving in.
You're in the Corps.
What outfit?
What dorm?
I was in Company A2.
And when we first moved there, we were in dorm three.
Within about a week, we moved to dorm one.
And I lived there for all of my freshman year.
I often say now that all the students refer to the dorms by name.
And back then, I guess none of us were too bright.
We all went by dorm number.
I guess we couldn't have remembered all the names.
Did your outfit have a nickname?
A Battery.
Company A2, A Battery Field Artillery.
They didn't have the unit designations as they did back in World War II, but that outfit had retained its designation.
It was an Army outfit.
Describe your room as a fish.
What was in there?
Two walls, a door, a window.
Absolutely no...
My goodness, when I looked at my daughter's dorm room as a freshman last year, her room looked like an electronics store compared to what mine was like.
It was very sparkly.
What furniture?
Beds, bunk beds.
There was a metal chest of drawers that each roommate got about two drawers or three drawers of it.
There was an old, each student had a desk and a chair with plastic sort of, I'm not sure what the material was, sort of like plastic arms in the back.
I think it was a wooden desk, although it may have been metal and I just don't remember.
And that was about it.
It was a sink built into the wall with a mirror.
I can still remember that, but that's about all you got.
Alright, and the toilet and
gang showers, gang toilets down the hall, two on each floor.
And freshmen could have a footlocker where you kept most of your stuff.
You lived out of your footlocker and you had a closet, a very small, very small closet.
And you could have a certain number of civilian things in there, but you really didn't have much need
Describe the typical weekday routine for a fish.
What time did you get up, what did you do, and what sequence?
I hadn't thought about this in years.
Probably got up about 6, although I may be wrong about that.
You wake up, have morning formation.
March to breakfast during morning formation.
Sophomores would inspect your uniform.
March to breakfast, eat breakfast, come back.
You usually have a little bit of time for last minute studying if you needed to, but mainly what you do is clean your room for inspection.
You go to class, come back, have lunch formation, march to lunch.
And then in the afternoon, if you had class, you'd go there.
Most of the people would try to
take that time in the afternoon to catch up on a little sleep if you could.
So usually there was more sleeping that went on in the dorm in the afternoon than at night.

And then in the evening you'd have evening formation, march to suppu, come back and have study time, call the quarters, study time, until about 10 o'clock, 10.30, and then it was lights out for freshmen.
Did you have any upperclassmen's room for which you were responsible?

the fish no uh i was i was pretty lucky i had a i had a i lived right next door to a senior who was from tarrant county he was a outstanding guy fine man ended up getting his phd in civil engineering at am and uh
And as a result of that, rather than suffering some of the horror stories that many other people suffered down there, I was spared a little bit of that because he was a very high class guy.
So I didn't have some of the abuse that other people had.
Can you describe any of the, what an outsider might call, hazing that went on?
I know for a fact that that sort of thing varied from outfit to outfit.
And we didn't have as much of it in my outfit.
There were some outfits that people would get their rear ends beat with broom handles.
I had a little bit of that, but not much.
Most of the hazing was the type that, well,
mental hazing.
There was usually some, if you didn't know a campusology question, you might have to do push-ups.
There were times when they'd take all the freshmen out and haze them with push-ups or sit-ups or something, but that was pretty much the extent of it, at least in my outfit.
In your outfit, were there any ever any retribution activities to strike back at a sophomore or junior or senior who took advantage of some fish?
I don't remember.
I'm sure if I really thought back about it, I probably would call some.
I'm not sure that I remember any specific ones.
I do know that there was always the situation at that time, sort of a tradition, that the freshmen would steal their company commander's footlocker.
And that was sort of an opportunity for the upperclassmen to, in an organized manner, haze the freshmen.
I seem to recall that in our outfit, the idea was that you were supposed to somehow get your CO's footlocker into the stadium for the Thanksgiving Day game, take it on the field, and leave it.
And the story that I seem to remember in my outfit was that
We did have a freshman who managed with one or two others to get our CO's footlocker into the stadium.
And of all things, it turned out that they happened to be seated near or somewhere around our CO's mother who wondered why her son's footlocker was with these other people.
But that was a chance for about a week or so of organized hazing.
And there was also the
Another example of sort of organized hazing was before the SMU game, there was always a requirement that freshmen wear spurs because we were playing the SMU Mustang.
Made out of?
Made out of beer bottle caps.
And that required a lot of effort.
I had a car.
It wasn't rare, but it was not common for people to have cars.
But...
I went with two or three of my fish buddies, and we went to one of the beer distributors in Bryan and asked if they had some old bottle caps, and they had some.
So we were able to maybe do a little better job than some of the other guys.
We got just all the bottle caps we wanted and took them back, and then you had to straighten them out.
and drill a hole in them and just a lot of work, just a lot of work to walk around the campus wearing those things.
They should put them on coat hangers?
Put them on, yeah, you'd strap them on, you'd affix them to coat hangers around the back of your shoes and then somehow hook them under.
I can't remember exactly how you did it.
You'd make a little apparatus and then tie them around so that they were attached to your shoes.
They'd make this god awful noise when you'd walk around campus.
Because I remember as an instructor trying to say to the students, OK, I know what week this is.
Try to keep your feet still during class.
Yeah, yeah.
Let's see.
Was your freshman year roommate a special official lady?
Was that a special relationship for you, a special friend?
No, actually, we didn't know each other.
We were just thrown together, and we got along well.
No, did he become a special friend?
No, not really, not really.
I saw him about 10 years ago, but he only stayed in the Corps for another year or so, and then left.
And so we didn't know.
Were there some special friends that you made in your outfit?
Yes, there were some.
As time progressed, I made, probably my best friends were not necessarily guys that were in my outfit.
I still see some of them at class reunions and things, but I guess my best friends were people that I, friends that I made my junior and senior year down there.
Let's see, dining hall.
Describe some of the dining hall routine for a corps member in Duncan.
Oh dear, you're taking me back a long way.
Freshmen had to give meal service, had to sit next to an upperclassman, had to give meal service.
You were seated family style, which means there were about, as I recall, probably eight people at a table.
Waiters would bring the food in bowls.
And it was the freshmen's duty to make sure that everybody had enough to eat, specifically the upperclassmen.
And they were responsible for organizing the food dishes to quarter more.
If you wanted something else to eat, you could always send it back.
They'd have to work with the waiters.
And sometimes if they had an upperclassman waiter, they'd get hazed by that upperclassman waiter just as much as they would the guys at their tables.
And freshmen really didn't get a chance to do much eating until the upperclassmen had left.
And then they had the rule that freshmen could walk around and just grab whatever they wanted to off any of the tables.
And so usually about 20 minutes after the meal had started, you'd look around and you'd find just isolated freshmen here and there.
And that's the way most of us kept from losing any more weight than we did, was by taking advantage of that and eating whatever we could.
Well, share with me, if you can, some of the nicknames for various food items.
Oh, golly.
Boy, I hadn't thought about this.
Oh, dear.
Gravy, beans, meat, milk, bread.
Let's see.
Dessert was kush.
That's an easy one.
Dessert was kush.
I remember that.
Let's see.
Meat was bull neck.
Milk was cow.
Shoot the cow.
Good gracious.
Ketchup?
Blood.
That's one of those things that's back there in my memory somewhere, but some guys probably brought their kids up teaching them those things, and I never did, so I can't.
Oh, I just thought of one that I'd not ask anybody else.
I've heard of stories where that some freshman forgot when he got home and used some A&M lingo at the table.
Did that happen to you?
No.
Some of the food terminology was not exactly etiquette that your mother would teach you.
Yeah, that's what I've heard.
And that the mother or father would say, what?
Yeah.
And it wasn't...
I knew of stories like that.
Do you remember, whether it involved you or not, do you remember any dining hall pranks, jokes?
Sure.
Share some.
Lots of times they would be seniors or juniors who would instruct other freshmen to crawl along the floor and

Everyone had to sit with their napkins tucked into their lap, and they'd give somebody a cigarette lighter and have them crawl along the floor and slide it up under a table and light somebody's napkin.
And of course, if you ever felt something like that, you could tell it was a freshman from some other outfit, so you wouldn't squeal on a fish buddy and tell the upperclassmen.
Usually at mealtime you were asked campusology questions by the sophomore or some other upperclassmen at your table.

And it always, if you had upperclassmen who were sports fans, they were always asking you questions about who was in the starting lineup for the Aggies or who was the high point man for the Aggies the night before or that sort of thing.
So you always had to be prepared for things like that.
Those were
Once you kind of got in a routine and learned the people that were sitting at your table, it could be kind of fun if you were with good people.
Please share any of the good bull jokes, pranks that you knew about while you were an undergraduate.
Like one year I had two or three students in my history 105 and they decided they would try to kidnap every Southwest Conference mascot.
Yeah, that was about the group of 1964.
Something like that, yeah.
I've got a friend who was in that class and he's told me about that.
Oh dear.
Did y'all, did you hear of any legendary pranks on a sophomore or a senior?
Well, there was...

I almost feel like I need to go off the record, but there was a classmate of mine, a good friend of mine, who lived in my dorm for about three years, who would go out before football weekends with his bow and arrow and would poach deer.
He'd freeze them in the headlights
And the coach would shoot him with a bow and arrow and dress, to clean him and dress him in the shower, drag him back to campus, clean him, dress him in the shower, cook him for outfit parties.
Oh my.
Now, was this in the Brazos County area where he killed the deer?
Yeah.
With a bow and arrow.
Yeah, and he was a pretty legendary guy like that.
Oh, I never heard that one.
When we're not taping, I'll tell you more about it sometime.

I can still remember that when I was in school, probably junior and senior year, there was a tendency toward making, in the dorm area, catapults using funnels with surgical tubing fixed through the tops of them.
And then you'd make water balloons.
stick them in the funnel and pull them back, and you'd fire water balloons across the quad at each other.
And what was the container of the water?
Just a funnel.
No.
Oh, just a funnel.
A funnel.
And you'd put a water balloon, and you'd fill it.
put water in the balloon.
Was that a true balloon?
Oh yeah.
Just fill the little balloon and then you stick them in a funnel, just a plain old plastic funnel like you can find anywhere.
You have a couple people hold on to each end of the surgical tubing, pull the funnel back and let it fly.
There were a lot of, back in the spring, there were a lot of water fights.
Of course there was always the band
the Corps versus the band.
There was always all kinds of things going on between them.
Let's see.
Drownouts?
Oh, yeah.
Yeah.
Oh, Babbo bombs?
Yeah.
Describe, as far as you know, describe the technology for Babbo bombing.
Well, let me think.
Basically, you get a, not a can, what do you call it, a container of Babbo
take the top off, insert a cherry bomb in it, and with a fuse, if I remember right, put the can back on, light the fuse.
All right, now was there still an airspace under doors at that point?
There was a little bit, yeah.
Okay, and then you'd roll it under there?
You couldn't quite get it all the way under there.
I remember there, we used to take, there was enough room between...
between the door and the door jam, that you could take a baseball bat, split right down the middle, and jam the baseball bat between those, and somebody inside the room couldn't get out.
That was used one time that I can recall.
I guess the statute of limitations inspired on a lot of these things.
One that I heard about was a roll of tea paper
soaked in water.
And I said, are you sure it was water?
Yes, it was water.
Then a babble bomb stuffed with paper and roll that under and blow it.
Oh, you could do that in the toilets.
The toilets had an air space.
Oh, no.
This was in the 40s.
Oh, in the 40s.
There was then a lot of air space.
And then hot weather, window up, first floor room, sandbag is door.
put the water hose in the window, turned on softly, and let the water get maybe a foot deep in the room.
But the person said, we didn't realize when that door was open where that water was going to go down the hallway and who was going to have to clean it up.
Yeah, yeah.
I didn't ever know about any of those, but yeah.
What about some good bull at football games or yell practices or anything?
Do you remember anything?
Or in class.
I spent about 30 years just kind of blocking some of those things out.
I'm kind of blanked on that.
Also, one other thing that comes back to me is I remember
Some of the guys in my outfit, they were sophomores, I guess, learned how to get around in the steam tunnels.
Where did the steam tunnels go?
Apparently all under the whole campus.
If I remember right, there was a place that you could get in.
I never went down there, but a couple of these guys did.
You could go over by the biology building.
It was a place that you could get down in there.
And the steam tunnels went all underneath the dorm areas.

And the idea was that you could, the idea was that ideally you could go down there, particularly under the band dorm, and find some way to get in there and you could work some mischief on the band of some type, I think.
But I don't remember exactly, I don't think there was anything catastrophic that happened.
But that's what happened to me.
I had a lot of guys with a lot of time on their hands.
How did your life change when you became a sophomore?
What was different about being a sophomore?
Well, the most immediate thing I remember is that my sophomore year, we moved.
Our outfit was in the Sabisa area.
They still had some core units over there.
And the most immediate thing was that we had an air-conditioned dorm.
So this would be the fall of 60?
That area was air conditioned.
My freshman year, the Duncan area was not air conditioned.
So that made everything more tolerable.
We parked over there.
I had a parking place that wasn't as far away as the freshman.
We used to call the freshman and sophomore lots the Hempstead and Avisota lot because they were down there near where the old bonfire field used to be.
which in retrospect wasn't all that far, but it seemed long.
But my sophomore year, it was a totally different orientation, on a different side of the campus.
And you were over by Northgate, so you could always go over there and buy things if you needed to.
There was shopping you could go to.
And it was different for me because I changed my major to accounting.
I nearly flunked out of starting out as an engineering major.
And so I changed my major to accounting and did much better.
So I always viewed my sophomore year as really a good year.
Let's try to zero in now on some of the academic.
When you came, you were planning to major in?
Engineering.
Engineering.
And what courses helped you decide you didn't want to do engineering?
Very simple.
I didn't think I would be good at engineering, but my father had been one.
I thought, well, I'll try it and see.

In the spring semester of my freshman year, I was taking 18 hours, which a lot of people did back then, and I made, on a three-point average, a three-point range, I made a 1.0, which doesn't sound too bad, but I still remember I made an A in PE, an A in military science, and an A in history.
One of the six, I think it was.
And then there may have been something else that I got some great points in.
I think I made a C, perhaps, in engineering drawing.
But then I had 12 other hours.
Chemistry, I made a D. Physics and calculus, I made an F.
So I decided right then that I didn't have an engineer's approach to things.
So you switched to accounting?
Switched to accounting.
All right.
And did that remain your major?
Yes.
I got my degree in accounting.
Who were the key advisors, teachers, whether in accounting or not, that you now look back upon as being important?
Sure.
In the business school,
Business school then was not nearly what it is now.
It is an excellent school now.
Then it was adequate, and they were working to make it better.
There was Carlton Stowie, who is still on the accounting faculty, was a young accounting instructor, and I had him for one of the accounting classes.
He was a good teacher.
There was another young accounting professor, Alan Porter, who was a very good...
professor and I remember learning quite a bit from him.

I think without question the best professor I had in business school was a man named Bill Luker and I still remember that business students then had to take two semesters of statistics and the first semester I took in the spring of my sophomore year
And I was a sophomore, and most of the other people in there were juniors and some seniors, I think.
And statistics was something that came easy for me.
I did very well in class.
But Dr. Luker was so interested in students' learning that an amazing thing happened.
When the fall semester of the next year came around and people were signing up for the
for the second semester of statistics, he told us in advance what class he'd be teaching.
And remarkably, virtually everyone who was in that other class signed up for his fall class.
And he walked in, and here was almost the same seating chart.
Everyone signed because he was a remarkably gifted teacher.
There were several other teachers, particularly in the liberal arts area, that I enjoyed.
I took several economics classes, excellent teachers.
Who?
Graham.
Senator Graham had started teaching then in history.
Dr. Calvin, I had him for 106, I believe.
He's still there.
Yeah, very good teacher, very good teacher.
took some English classes that I enjoyed.

And so while A&M is essentially a technology-oriented agriculture and engineering school, it was in the liberal arts area that I found several teachers who were very interesting that really gave me appreciation for those things.
If you needed advice and counseling, to whom did you turn?
I'm trying to think.
Depending upon the time, well, I can tell you that the person that gave me a lot of advice when I was trying to decide about going to law school was Wayne Stark.
I never was active in the MSC programs that Wayne had, but I knew him.
I think somehow my parents had been down there one time and met him.
He used to always hang out in the coffee shop at the MSC.
I got to know him.
He was always trying to get people to go to Harvard Law School.
I don't think I was high octane enough for that, but he was very encouraging about those kinds of things.
He was a particularly good man.
Did you ever get the green couch treatment from him?
No.
Do you know what I'm talking about?
I've heard that.
But no, I didn't.
All of my involvement with Mr. Stark was just in different discussions.
I went on some of his MSC student leader trips.
Oh, did you?
Yeah.
Describe.
The one that I can particularly remember was when we were seniors when we went to Houston.
He gave Aggies from College Station the opportunity to do things that probably most of us hadn't done before.
